536//10=88005553.6 â†’88005553.Which matches all samples.Thus, the code is correct.","deepseek_solution":"To solve this problem, we need to determine the number of integers ( x ) such that ( 1 le x le n ) and ( x ) is \\"interesting\\". An integer ( x ) is considered interesting if the sum of the digits of ( x+1 ) is less than the sum of the digits of ( x ). ApproachThe key insight is that a number ( x ) is interesting if and only if it ends in one or more trailing 9s. When such a number is incremented by 1, all trailing 9s become zeros, leading to a significant reduction in the sum of its digits. For example, the number 999 becomes 1000 when incremented, reducing the digit sum from 27 to 1.To efficiently count such numbers up to ( n ), observe that every number ending in 9 can be written in the form ( 10k - 1 ). This means there is exactly one such number in every block of 10 consecutive numbers (e.g., 9, 19, 29, ..., 99, etc.). Thus, the count of interesting numbers up to ( n ) can be computed as ((n + 1) // 10), which gives the number of such blocks. Solution Code\`\`\`pythont = int(input())for _ in range(t):    n = int(input())    print((n + 1) // 10)\`\`\` Explanation1. Reading Input: The first input line contains the number of test cases ( t ).2. Processing Each Test Case: For each test case, read the integer ( n ).3. Counting Interesting Numbers: For each ( n ), compute the count of numbers ending in 9 using the formula ((n + 1) // 10). This formula effectively counts how many numbers ending in 9 exist between 1 and ( n ).This approach ensures that the solution is efficient and runs in constant time ( O(1) ) for each test case, making it suitable for large values of ( n ) up to ( 10^9 )."},{"problem":"Chefland is a 1D city where each of the N houses is located at a distinct positive integer coordinate A_{1}, A_{2}, ldots A_{N}. The chef is planning to create K hills in the city. Note that two hills cannot be present at the same location but the location of hills and houses can overlap and each hill will also be at any integer (positive, negative or zero) coordinate. Each citizen would want to travel to the farthest hill from his house. Travelling will create air pollution and Chef wants to minimise the total pollution in the city. Help Chef find the minimum sum of distance travelled by everyone. In other words, help Chef create the hills at optimal locations, so that the sum of the distance of every house to the hill farthest from it is minimum possible.------ Input: ------First line will contain T, number of testcases. Then the testcases follow. Each testcase contains two lines of input.First line contains 2 integers N, K separated by a space.Second line contains N integers A_{1}, A_{2}, ldots, A_{N}, representing the location of the houses. ------ Output: ------For each testcase, find the minimum possible sum of distances if Chef creates the hills at optimal locations, in a separate line.------ Constraints  ------1 â‰¤ T â‰¤ 101 â‰¤ N, K â‰¤ 10^{5}1 â‰¤ A_{i} â‰¤ 10^{9}A_{i} < A_{i + 1} forall valid i----- Sample Input 1 ------ 33 11 2 31 512 21 5----- Sample Output 1 ------ 225----- explanation 1 ------ TestCase 1: Optimal solution includes creating hill at 2. Its distance from the house at coordinate 1 is 1, and so is its distance from the house at coordinate 3. Its distance from the house at coordinate 2 is 0. Thus, total distance is 1+0+1=2.TestCase 2: Optimal solution includes creating hills at {-1, 0, 1, 2, 3 }. The farthest hills from the house at coordinate 1 are at coordinates -1 and 3. The citizen can choose to travel to any of them, and the distance shall be 2.TestCase 3: Optimal solution includes creating hills at {1, 2 } or {4, 5 }.","deepseek_reasoning":"Okay, let's try to figure out this problem. So the problem is about placing K hills such that for each house, we take the farthest hill from it, and sum all those distances. And we need to minimize that sum. Hmm, that's interesting.Wait, so each house's 